  pages     = {127--152},
  abstract  = {This chapter describes several emerging therapy modalities and provides a broad overview of the evidence for each. First, it describes schema therapy as an emerging "third wave" psychotherapy that shows a great deal of promise. It then explores interpersonal psychotherapy (IPT), an important adaptation of integrated psychodynamic psychotherapies that has recently found significant traction among evidence-based therapies that can be task shifted to lay counselors. Thereafter, it provides an overview of problem-solving therapy (PST) as an important derivative of cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) that has made significant inroads where task-shifting interventions in low- and middle-income countries (LMIC) are concerned. This is followed by a description of some of the innovative approaches promulgated by the World Health Organization in its mhGAP Intervention Guide for mental, neurological and substance use disorders in non-specialized health settings, Version 2.0 (mhGAP-IG) (WHO, 2016). The chapter explores novel methods of delivery, with a focus on the employment of technology. It concludes by highlighting some of the gaps in the current research and make recommendations concerning the way forward. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)},
