  number    = {5},
  pages     = {495},
  volume    = {64},
  abstract  = {This article focuses psychiatric rehabilitation that has been developed, studied, and implemented primarily if not exclusively in urban settings, where formal and funded services are much more available than in rural and remote communities. The community mental health program provides services to sites located in remote communities. The rural or remote psychiatric rehabilitation (rPSR) program is supported by academic psychiatrists from Southern Canada, who provide fly-in and telehealth consultations to the program and to local family physicians regarding the program's adult service users. The program also provides psychotherapies to service users and in-person and distance education to its clinicians. A particularly important component of the program is the use of telehealth technologies, which offer innovative ways of solving some of the struggles in accessing services from remote or rural communities. In spite of some challenges, rPSR is promising as a means to facilitate recovery of people with psychiatric disability in their rural and remote environments of choice. It requires clinical, administrative, and other strategies beyond those of standard psychiatric rehabilitation, such as task shifting and coverage by clinicians across proximal sites. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
